  "accepted_answer": {
    "post_number": 4,
    "username": "Herohtar",
    "name": "",
    "excerpt": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"nickster\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"74645\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/2acd7d/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> nickster:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Hence, I have the worry that the Signal app has been hacked in a serious way to distribute these legimate looking messages.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>No. If the app itself were hacked in such a way as to be able to directly ask for your recovery code then whatever hacker would already have access to all your message content and wouldn\u2019t need to ask.</p>\n<p>Those are legitimate reminders to help users remember/verify that their recovery information is valid.</p>\n<p>A phishing attempt would generally be in the form of a <em>message</em> from another user who was impersonating Signal (eg, they might have the Signal icon as a profile picture and try to have a display name that says something like \u201cSignal Admin\u201d and put emoji that look like the verified checkmark in it, etc)</p>"
  },
